For non-stationary data, ACF drops to 0 relatively slowly, because non-stationary data may still appear highly correlated with previous observations, indicating that time component still plays an important role. The diagram above shows the ACF of the original time series data, which decreases slowly thus very likely to be non-stationary.

In[8]:
def check_stationary(data:pd.DataFrame, decomposition_period = 1):
    sns.lineplot(data = data, x='index' , y="finance", linewidth=1.5,color='#0C2D57')
    plt.xlabel('\nYear')
    plt.ylabel("Monthly Popularity\n")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.title('Monthly Popularity of Finance \n(Stationarity)')
    plt.show()
    
    _, pvalue,_,_,_,_ = adfuller(data['finance'],autolag='AIC')
    print(f"P-value for transformed data stationary check:\n{pvalue}")

    
    decomposition = seasonal_decompose(x=data['finance'], model='additive', period = decomposition_period) 
    decomposition.plot()

    fig, axes = plt.subplots(2,1,figsize=(20, 10))
    
    tsaplots.plot_acf(data['finance'], lags=60, color='#5D3587', ax=axes[0]) 
    tsaplots.plot_pacf(data['finance'], lags=60, color='#FC6736', ax=axes[1]) 
    fig.show()
In[9]:
trend_diff = (q1_data.diff(periods=1)).dropna(inplace=False)
seasonal_diff = (trend_diff - trend_diff.shift(12)).dropna(inplace=False)
diff_data = seasonal_diff.reset_index()
check_stationary(diff_data)

P-value for transformed data stationary check:
1.4238895117383722e-06

By using ADF test , we found that p value is far below 0.05. Therefore, it indicates it is highly likely that transformed time series data is stationary.

The visualization above indicates that the time series trend has been limited and its mean values conatants over time, suggesting that the data is stationary. Also seasonality is 0 and residuals are 0.

1.c

The figure above (1.b) shows the ACF of transformed time series data, which decreases rapidly to 0 and appear to have constant mean, thus stationary.

ACF can be used for determining the q value for the MA(q) model. It is typically selected as the first lagged value of which the ACF drops to nearly 0 for the first time, i.e. q = 3 PACF can be used for determining the p value for the AR(p) model since it visualizes the direct contribution of the past observation to the current observations.

We can observe that when lag = 3 the PACF is almost 0. We will select the AR(p)-values by when the PACF falls within the significant threshold (blue area) for the first time, i.e. p = 3. In the lecture we said values should be from the set {0,1,2}, so we will test p = 2 as well. We will select the q-values by when the ACF is first dropping near 0 for the first time, i.e. q = 2. We also tested different parameters for checking, for instance p=12 for autocorrletion was detected after few shots of other values, where the correlogram presented spickes in 12,24,ect..

In[69]:
def res_plot(model,model_name):
    model_df = pd.DataFrame(model.resid.iloc[12:], columns = ['error']).reset_index()
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(16,5))
    plt.scatter(x=model_df['index'], y=model_df["error"])
    plt.axhline(y=0, color="#C21292", linestyle="--",linewidth=2)
    props = dict(facecolor='#C21292', edgecolor='black', boxstyle='round,pad=0.2',alpha=.7)
    plt.text(0.95,0.9,f"BIC: {round(model.bic,4)}",fontsize=14,color='white',va='center',ha='center', bbox=props, transform=ax.transAxes)
    plt.title(f"SARIMAX\n\n{model_name}")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

    sns.lineplot(data = data, x='index' , y="baseball", linewidth=1.5,color='#0C2D57')

In[195]:
from prophet import Prophet

q2_data["y"] = q2_data["baseball"]
q2_data["ds"] = q2_data.index

model = Prophet(seasonality_mode='additive').fit(q2_data)
future = model.make_future_dataframe(periods=365)
forecast = model.predict(future)

residuals = [true-pred for true,pred in zip (q2_data['y'], forecast['yhat'][:len(q2_data)])]

fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(10, 6))
axes = axes.flatten()

axes[0].plot(residuals)

axes[1].hist(residuals, bins=20, density=True)
xmin, xmax = axes[1].get_xlim()
x = np.linspace(xmin, xmax, 100)
p = stats.norm.pdf(x, np.mean(residuals), np.std(residuals))
axes[1].plot(x, p, 'k', linewidth=2)

stats.probplot(residuals, dist="norm", plot=axes[2])
tsaplots.plot_acf(residuals, ax=axes[3], lags=20)


axes[0].set_title('Residuals')
axes[1].set_title('Histogram + Density')
axes[2].set_title('Normal Q-Q Plot')
axes[3].set_title('Autocorrelation')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

In[260]:
def model_results(model):
    print(model.summary())
    model.plot_diagnostics(lags=24,figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
In[261]:
def res_plot(model,model_name):
    model_df = pd.DataFrame(model.resid.iloc[12:], columns = ['error']).reset_index()
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(16,5))
    plt.scatter(x=model_df['index'], y=model_df["error"])
    plt.axhline(y=0, color="#C21292", linestyle="--",linewidth=2)
    props = dict(facecolor='#C21292', edgecolor='black', boxstyle='round,pad=0.2',alpha=.7)
    plt.text(0.95,0.9,f"BIC: {round(model.bic,4)}",fontsize=14,color='white',va='center',ha='center', bbox=props, transform=ax.transAxes)
    plt.title(f"SARIMAX\n\n{model_name}")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

from statsmodels.tsa.holtwinters import ExponentialSmoothing

exp_smooth = ExponentialSmoothing(q3_data, seasonal_periods=12, trend='add', seasonal='add') 
exp_smooth_fit = exp_smooth.fit()

fig,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(18, 5))
ax.plot(q3_data.index, q3_data['retail'], label="Observed",color='#FB88B4')
exp_smooth_fit.forecast(12).plot(label= "Prediction", linewidth=3,color='#FB2576')
ax.set_xlabel("\nYear")
